00:05:10.259 --> 00:05:12.050
We are going to talk
about form perception.

00:05:13.760 --> 00:05:18.870
This is a topic that,
even at this stage,

00:05:18.870 --> 00:05:21.670
we still only have
rather limited knowledge

00:05:21.670 --> 00:05:27.270
about how the brain is
capable of carrying out

00:05:27.270 --> 00:05:29.230
the perception of form.

00:05:29.230 --> 00:05:32.000
And we are going to look at
some inferences and some ideas

00:05:32.000 --> 00:05:32.860
about it.

00:05:32.860 --> 00:05:36.830
And I will also provide you with
a brief historical background.

00:05:36.830 --> 00:05:40.440
Because this has been a
topic of tremendous interest

00:05:40.440 --> 00:05:46.090
for people for centuries,
trying to understand just

00:05:46.090 --> 00:05:52.710
how we are capable of seeing
forms, shapes, patterns.

00:05:52.710 --> 00:05:57.810
All right, so the
first influential idea

00:05:57.810 --> 00:06:01.430
that emerged about this
is called structuralism.

00:06:02.490 --> 00:06:09.210
And this idea actually took
place in the late 19th century.

00:06:10.260 --> 00:06:14.890
And one of the prime proponents
was a fellow called Titchener.

00:06:14.890 --> 00:06:19.540
And they had, in trying to come
to grips with how we do this,

00:06:19.540 --> 00:06:24.150
had a rather basic
idea, much like building

00:06:24.150 --> 00:06:25.840
a house with bricks.

00:06:25.840 --> 00:06:29.970
The idea was that
perception is an aggregate

00:06:29.970 --> 00:06:31.049
of simple elements.

00:06:31.049 --> 00:06:33.590
We just have a whole bunch of
elements that you put together.

00:06:33.590 --> 00:06:38.310
And that generates a
more complex precept, OK.

00:06:38.310 --> 00:06:41.570
The problem with this approach,
well, the first problem

00:06:41.570 --> 00:06:44.306
was that they began
to do experiments.

00:06:45.330 --> 00:06:49.640
And they asked subjects
to try to divorce

00:06:49.640 --> 00:06:52.140
a personal impression of
anything they looked at.

00:06:52.140 --> 00:06:54.400
But to sort of
physically describe it.

00:06:54.400 --> 00:06:56.990
So for example, if you
looked at an apple,

00:06:56.990 --> 00:07:01.350
how do you have the
idea that it's an apple?

00:07:01.350 --> 00:07:04.880
And so they said, well,
it has say, four colors.

00:07:04.880 --> 00:07:07.470
And so the person would
list four colors and said

00:07:07.470 --> 00:07:09.050
would have several shades.

00:07:09.050 --> 00:07:11.980
And put all those
together, add them all up,

00:07:11.980 --> 00:07:13.620
and that equals apple.

00:07:14.700 --> 00:07:17.300
Well, that was the idea then.

00:07:17.300 --> 00:07:19.790
And when they did
this systematically,

00:07:19.790 --> 00:07:21.630
and the thing became
almost ridiculous.

00:07:21.630 --> 00:07:24.970
Because they came up
with more than 40,000

00:07:24.970 --> 00:07:28.790
elementary sensations,
thinking that somehow you

00:07:28.790 --> 00:07:31.800
puts these elementary
sensations together,

00:07:31.800 --> 00:07:33.910
40,000 of them,
and that gives us

00:07:33.910 --> 00:07:36.550
a sense of an apple,
or banana, or whatever.

00:07:37.670 --> 00:07:42.260
Now as soon as this sort
of became well known,

00:07:42.260 --> 00:07:46.180
a lot of opposition arose.

00:07:46.180 --> 00:07:48.450
And one of the most
famous ones then

00:07:48.450 --> 00:07:50.360
was the opposition
that was brought

00:07:50.360 --> 00:07:51.973
about by Gestalt psychologists.

00:07:52.980 --> 00:07:57.720
And the first consideration that
I want to sort of bring up here

00:07:57.720 --> 00:07:59.480
is a rather simple picture.

00:07:59.480 --> 00:08:01.800
Here's a picture
everybody looks at that.

00:08:01.800 --> 00:08:03.050
OK, what did you see there?

00:08:04.780 --> 00:08:06.800
You saw a car, right?

00:08:06.800 --> 00:08:09.710
Now if you look at it,
I mean this is actually

00:08:09.710 --> 00:08:11.650
a picture of a car,
all right, but it's

00:08:11.650 --> 00:08:15.700
interrupted by all these
vertical bars here.

00:08:15.700 --> 00:08:20.320
And yet we're able to
infer that it's a car.

00:08:20.320 --> 00:08:24.090
And so the question comes
up, how do you do this?

00:08:24.090 --> 00:08:27.000
I mean, you can't simply
just add up a bunch of bricks

00:08:27.000 --> 00:08:28.310
and say it's a car.

00:08:28.310 --> 00:08:30.710
Because there's all
this interruption.

00:08:30.710 --> 00:08:34.190
And most things that
we see in the world,

00:08:34.190 --> 00:08:37.490
we see in a
discontinuous fashion.

00:08:37.490 --> 00:08:41.620
And as a result of this,
the Gestalt psychologists,

00:08:41.620 --> 00:08:45.830
which happened sort
of in the 1920s,

00:08:45.830 --> 00:08:47.860
began to think about
this whole problem

00:08:47.860 --> 00:08:49.470
in a very different way.

00:08:49.470 --> 00:08:51.145
And they made a
tremendous influence.

00:08:52.530 --> 00:08:56.100
And they came up
with these new ideas

00:08:56.100 --> 00:08:59.830
of how we create the
perception of form.

00:08:59.830 --> 00:09:02.070
The founder of the
Gestalt psychology

00:09:02.070 --> 00:09:04.750
is a fellow called
Max Wertheimer.

00:09:06.070 --> 00:09:10.270
So now, you can look this
up in Wikipedia, by the way,

00:09:10.270 --> 00:09:13.370
if you look at
them more closely,

00:09:13.370 --> 00:09:20.100
they came up with a few basic
principles of organization.

00:09:20.100 --> 00:09:22.930
And they call this grouping.

00:09:22.930 --> 00:09:26.600
They argue that in the brain,
somehow we group things up.

00:09:26.600 --> 00:09:29.800
And one of the things we group
has to do with proximity.

00:09:29.800 --> 00:09:32.500
Another one has to
do with similarity,

00:09:32.500 --> 00:09:36.500
another one with common motion,
another one with closure,

00:09:36.500 --> 00:09:39.050
and another one with
figure-ground perception.

00:09:39.050 --> 00:09:42.190
This last one I'm going to talk
about at the end of today's

00:09:42.190 --> 00:09:43.310
presentation.

00:09:43.310 --> 00:09:46.170
But now I'm going to give you
an example of these top two.

00:09:48.560 --> 00:09:52.420
All right, so the most
important conclusion

00:09:52.420 --> 00:09:55.810
that they had come to which was
very much against structuralism

00:09:55.810 --> 00:09:58.680
is that the whole
that you see is

00:09:58.680 --> 00:10:00.880
different from the
sum of its parts.

00:10:00.880 --> 00:10:03.310
Somehow, there is
an active process

00:10:03.310 --> 00:10:07.490
that creates our ability to
see something that is not

00:10:07.490 --> 00:10:10.220
evidenced from its
individual parts.

00:10:10.220 --> 00:10:13.930
Now here is an example of
what these principles are.

00:10:13.930 --> 00:10:18.240
Grouping by proximity, so
here we have a bunch of dots.

00:10:18.240 --> 00:10:21.380
And if you'll put them
closer together vertically,

00:10:21.380 --> 00:10:24.150
you see a bunch of
vertical lines essentially.

00:10:24.150 --> 00:10:26.760
And if you put them closer
together horizontally,

00:10:26.760 --> 00:10:28.760
you see a bunch
of vertical lines,

00:10:28.760 --> 00:10:30.756
horizontal lines,
vertical lines.

00:10:30.756 --> 00:10:31.490
Yeah?

00:10:31.490 --> 00:10:36.980
So we group things
due to proximity.

00:10:36.980 --> 00:10:40.170
Another reason we group
things is shown here,

00:10:40.170 --> 00:10:45.610
is we group things according to
shape, or similarity of shape,

00:10:45.610 --> 00:10:47.000
I should really say.

00:10:47.000 --> 00:10:48.850
And here what we
have, you can readily

00:10:48.850 --> 00:10:58.190
see a group of nine disks here,
and a group of nine triangles.

00:10:58.190 --> 00:11:01.640
And if they're not all
the same as down here,

00:11:01.640 --> 00:11:04.460
then you have much more
difficulty grouping it.

00:11:04.460 --> 00:11:07.970
So there's a strong tendency
that we group things together

00:11:07.970 --> 00:11:09.440
that are similar.

00:11:09.440 --> 00:11:11.580
So these are some
general principles

00:11:11.580 --> 00:11:15.120
of how we organize
our visual percepts.

00:11:15.120 --> 00:11:17.680
So now we can look at some
more of these examples.

00:11:20.830 --> 00:11:23.780
In doing this, we
are now going to try

00:11:23.780 --> 00:11:27.980
to be able to say a bit
more about the brain itself.

00:11:27.980 --> 00:11:33.030
And in doing so, it's evident
that the three major theories

00:11:33.030 --> 00:11:37.230
that try to deal with how
the brain does it, according

00:11:37.230 --> 00:11:40.070
to the first of
these, form perception

00:11:40.070 --> 00:11:43.610
is accomplished by neurons
that respond selectively

00:11:43.610 --> 00:11:46.280
to line segments of
different orientations.

00:11:46.280 --> 00:11:49.400
Now that theory,
obviously, is the outgrowth

00:11:49.400 --> 00:11:56.770
of what we talked about when it
was discovered that in V1, we

00:11:56.770 --> 00:11:59.750
have orientation
selected neurons.

00:11:59.750 --> 00:12:01.930
And this orientation
selectivity is something

00:12:01.930 --> 00:12:04.230
that you see in
several progressively

00:12:04.230 --> 00:12:08.400
higher visual areas, as if
everything in the world out

00:12:08.400 --> 00:12:12.190
there was broken down into
oriented line segments, which

00:12:12.190 --> 00:12:16.750
are then somehow put together
according to there orientation

00:12:16.750 --> 00:12:18.210
to enable us to see shapes.

00:12:18.210 --> 00:12:19.620
So that's one theory.

00:12:19.620 --> 00:12:23.500
Another theory is that form
perception is accomplished

00:12:23.500 --> 00:12:29.490
by spatial mapping of the visual
scene onto the visual cortex.

00:12:29.490 --> 00:12:31.580
And I will elaborate
on each of these.

00:12:31.580 --> 00:12:34.960
And the third theory is one that
form perception is accomplished

00:12:34.960 --> 00:12:38.710
by virtue of Fourier analysis.

00:12:38.710 --> 00:12:44.580
So let us first then
turn to form perception,

00:12:44.580 --> 00:12:49.750
supposedly based on breaking
down the visual scene

00:12:49.750 --> 00:12:52.180
into oriented line segments.

00:12:52.180 --> 00:12:54.940
Now, one of the big
problems with this

00:12:54.940 --> 00:13:03.300
is that when you look
at a famous art work

00:13:03.300 --> 00:13:10.920
that you see in every day
in the Wall Street Journal,

00:13:10.920 --> 00:13:13.370
there is an artist who
created this originally.

00:13:13.370 --> 00:13:17.750
And he created faces
like this using only dots

00:13:17.750 --> 00:13:20.120
and varied the spatial
frequency of the dots,

00:13:20.120 --> 00:13:21.360
as you can see here.

00:13:22.410 --> 00:13:25.150
This happens to be a
person called Larry Poons.

00:13:25.150 --> 00:13:27.120
I'm sure none of you
have heard of him.

00:13:27.120 --> 00:13:30.680
But here was one of the
pictures many years ago

00:13:30.680 --> 00:13:32.280
in the Wall Street Journal.

00:13:32.280 --> 00:13:36.150
And even today, as I say, you
can see faces created this way.

00:13:36.150 --> 00:13:38.700
And you can readily
recognize them,

00:13:38.700 --> 00:13:41.960
even though there are no
oriented line segments here.

00:13:41.960 --> 00:13:46.300
And in fact, if you sort
of squint up and you three

00:13:46.300 --> 00:13:48.320
quarter ways close your
eyes, so you can't even

00:13:48.320 --> 00:13:50.720
see the dots anymore,
you can still

00:13:50.720 --> 00:13:52.670
make out that face
very, very clearly.

00:13:54.000 --> 00:13:57.330
That's because the spatial
frequency effect here

00:13:57.330 --> 00:13:58.880
is very important,
and the degree

00:13:58.880 --> 00:14:02.780
of shading, meaning that
this involves rather low

00:14:02.780 --> 00:14:05.650
spatial frequency
analyses, rather than

00:14:05.650 --> 00:14:11.870
the analysis of particular
orientations of line segments.

00:14:11.870 --> 00:14:21.080
Now this particular
analysis has its counterpart

00:14:21.080 --> 00:14:23.900
in the observation that
many of you have seen.

00:14:23.900 --> 00:14:29.670
When you look at a person's
face on television,

00:14:29.670 --> 00:14:31.750
and they want to
prevent you from being

00:14:31.750 --> 00:14:35.184
able to see that face because
it's confidential or something,

00:14:35.184 --> 00:14:35.850
what do they do?

00:14:36.987 --> 00:14:37.695
Anybody remember?

00:14:39.630 --> 00:14:41.240
What you do is
you put up a bunch

00:14:41.240 --> 00:14:47.890
of squares of different
spatial frequencies.

00:14:47.890 --> 00:14:52.560
And each square is comprised
of the mean illumination

00:14:52.560 --> 00:14:55.170
level of the actual face.

00:14:55.170 --> 00:14:58.930
If you do that, this high
frequency information

00:14:58.930 --> 00:15:01.890
is something that
interferes with your ability

00:15:01.890 --> 00:15:03.210
to analyze face.

00:15:03.210 --> 00:15:05.850
So to give you an example
of this, I'm sure all of you

00:15:05.850 --> 00:15:08.590
have seen this, but
mainly I show you this.

00:15:08.590 --> 00:15:10.280
Here we have this example.

00:15:10.280 --> 00:15:14.010
How many of you can tell
who these people are here?

00:15:15.050 --> 00:15:17.350
I guess nobody can, right?

00:15:17.350 --> 00:15:20.780
Now then what we
can do is we can

00:15:20.780 --> 00:15:23.250
increase the frequency of these.

00:15:23.250 --> 00:15:24.250
Here it is.

00:15:24.250 --> 00:15:26.550
And it's still very
difficult to tell.

00:15:26.550 --> 00:15:29.180
And now I'm going to show
you the actual photograph.

00:15:29.180 --> 00:15:32.710
And what I'm curious about is
how many of these two people

00:15:32.710 --> 00:15:33.700
you actually know.

00:15:34.720 --> 00:15:36.200
I can tell you
right away, they're

00:15:36.200 --> 00:15:41.520
extremely famous
actors and actresses.

00:15:41.520 --> 00:15:44.217
Who recognizes these people?

00:15:44.217 --> 00:15:45.300
How many of you recognize?

00:15:45.300 --> 00:15:46.630
Let me see your hand.

00:15:46.630 --> 00:15:48.480
Only a few people recognize it.

00:15:48.480 --> 00:15:51.330
That's how quickly time goes by.

00:15:51.330 --> 00:15:54.600
These were the most central,
most exciting, best known

00:15:54.600 --> 00:15:57.040
people in the movies.

00:15:58.120 --> 00:16:04.560
And this is Humphrey
Bogart, Ingrid Bergman.

00:16:04.560 --> 00:16:07.760
OK, so these are these
two very famous people

00:16:07.760 --> 00:16:12.110
whose faces were obstructed
by this and by this using

00:16:12.110 --> 00:16:18.550
these high contrast edges
that obscure your ability

00:16:18.550 --> 00:16:21.980
to smoothly analyze faces.

00:16:21.980 --> 00:16:33.950
So that then suggests that this
idea that we extensively use

00:16:33.950 --> 00:16:43.790
oriented line segments
to analyze faces at least

00:16:43.790 --> 00:16:47.570
is an insufficient
explanation of how

00:16:47.570 --> 00:16:51.790
the brain processes shapes.

00:16:51.790 --> 00:16:55.565
Now another idea is so-called
topographic mapping.

00:16:57.440 --> 00:17:00.080
This idea I'm sure
you can already

00:17:00.080 --> 00:17:02.480
reject on the basis
of what I told you

00:17:02.480 --> 00:17:06.960
about how the visual
system is laid out.

00:17:06.960 --> 00:17:08.720
But now I'm going
to belabor that

00:17:08.720 --> 00:17:10.650
so that you can
follow it closely.

00:17:10.650 --> 00:17:13.369
Here we have a
runner, of course.

00:17:13.369 --> 00:17:17.079
And here we have a monkey brain
to make it easy to understand.

00:17:17.079 --> 00:17:21.140
And the idea here there is
that this image, once it

00:17:21.140 --> 00:17:25.770
was discovered that the
visual field is laid out

00:17:25.770 --> 00:17:29.030
topographically in
the visual cortex,

00:17:29.030 --> 00:17:33.800
the idea was that what
happens is somehow,

00:17:33.800 --> 00:17:37.480
and I may be am unfair
to poke fun of it,

00:17:37.480 --> 00:17:41.240
but the idea is
that the mind can

00:17:41.240 --> 00:17:47.150
look at the creation of this
image on the cortical surface

00:17:47.150 --> 00:17:47.650
there.

00:17:49.130 --> 00:17:52.190
And thereby, it can identify.

00:17:52.190 --> 00:17:55.180
OK, it's almost
like a photograph,

00:17:55.180 --> 00:17:56.690
looking at a photograph.

00:17:56.690 --> 00:18:01.320
In this case the mind looks at
the photograph, so to speak,

00:18:01.320 --> 00:18:02.850
on the cortical surface.

00:18:02.850 --> 00:18:05.470
So they thought at
the time is that this

00:18:05.470 --> 00:18:07.250
is what you have there, OK.

00:18:07.250 --> 00:18:10.310
That's the imprint
of this image.

00:18:10.310 --> 00:18:12.290
And indeed, you say,
oh my goodness, that's

00:18:12.290 --> 00:18:13.000
just like that.

00:18:13.000 --> 00:18:17.210
Therefore, I can recognize that
person, and so on and so on.

00:18:17.210 --> 00:18:20.120
Well, I mean that's a cute idea.

00:18:20.120 --> 00:18:22.400
But then when you
take into account

00:18:22.400 --> 00:18:27.280
this has been discovered
subsequently to these ideas,

00:18:27.280 --> 00:18:33.700
that the topographic
layout in the visual cortex

00:18:33.700 --> 00:18:41.320
is actually not one to one
because of the magnification

00:18:41.320 --> 00:18:42.450
factor.

00:18:42.450 --> 00:18:45.060
So let's look at
that in some detail.

00:18:45.060 --> 00:18:51.410
Here is an actual reconstruction
of the monkey area V1 here.

00:18:52.490 --> 00:18:55.170
And here is the visual field.

00:18:55.170 --> 00:18:58.665
And we are going to
put these red arrows

00:18:58.665 --> 00:19:00.740
in the contralateral hemifield.

00:19:00.740 --> 00:19:03.030
Now remember what
I told you before,

00:19:03.030 --> 00:19:06.120
that if you look at
the visual scene,

00:19:06.120 --> 00:19:09.210
you can imagine your eyes
being vertically cut in half.

00:19:09.210 --> 00:19:12.350
And you have a nasal
and temporal hemiretina.

00:19:12.350 --> 00:19:18.360
And the one which is
contralateral hemifield

00:19:18.360 --> 00:19:22.270
crosses over and gets into
this half of the brain.

00:19:22.270 --> 00:19:25.100
And this one crosses
over to that half.

00:19:25.100 --> 00:19:28.720
So now if you do this and
take the magnification factor

00:19:28.720 --> 00:19:33.750
into account, you
look at these arrows,

00:19:33.750 --> 00:19:35.850
which are all
identical in size, OK.

00:19:35.850 --> 00:19:39.430
There are one, two, three,
four, five, six, seven of them.

00:19:39.430 --> 00:19:43.940
What you can see here
is the actual impression

00:19:43.940 --> 00:19:46.310
on the cortical
surface of the neurons

00:19:46.310 --> 00:19:50.250
that are being activated
by this look like this,

00:19:50.250 --> 00:19:53.480
nothing like those arrows there.

00:19:53.480 --> 00:19:56.300
And in fact, the central
arrow is much bigger

00:19:56.300 --> 00:19:59.420
because of the huge
magnification factor.

00:19:59.420 --> 00:20:05.790
Now this is already
creates a major problem

00:20:05.790 --> 00:20:11.890
in trying to believe in
that particular theory,

00:20:11.890 --> 00:20:13.910
the topographic mapping theory.

00:20:13.910 --> 00:20:18.180
But now, if instead,
you put those arrows

00:20:18.180 --> 00:20:21.520
halfway across each of
the hemispheres like that,

00:20:21.520 --> 00:20:23.720
then whatever is on
this side goes here.

00:20:23.720 --> 00:20:25.570
Whatever is on this
side goes there.

00:20:25.570 --> 00:20:28.140
And this is the impression
that is created.

00:20:29.600 --> 00:20:31.996
And my goodness, you
create that impression.

00:20:34.030 --> 00:20:36.234
And you say to yourself, my god.

00:20:36.234 --> 00:20:37.650
If that's the case,
how come I can

00:20:37.650 --> 00:20:41.240
see seven straight
arrows of equal size

00:20:41.240 --> 00:20:44.740
when this is the impression that
is being created in the brain?

00:20:44.740 --> 00:20:52.080
So therefore, obviously, they
are not using a topographic map

00:20:52.080 --> 00:20:54.180
to analyze the
visual scene at all.

00:20:56.150 --> 00:20:58.800
Now this can be driven
home even further.

00:20:58.800 --> 00:21:00.780
Let me make another point here.

00:21:00.780 --> 00:21:04.670
Here we have a monkey visual
cortex again from the rear.

00:21:04.670 --> 00:21:06.600
Here is the visual
field laid out.

00:21:06.600 --> 00:21:11.890
And if here we put in a bunch
of dots in a circular fashion,

00:21:11.890 --> 00:21:14.037
this is the activation there.

00:21:14.037 --> 00:21:15.370
Now you say, oh, that's not bad.

00:21:15.370 --> 00:21:17.260
That looks like a circle.

00:21:17.260 --> 00:21:23.060
But then if you put it along
the midline, half and half,

00:21:23.060 --> 00:21:25.300
then this is the
actual activation.

00:21:25.300 --> 00:21:29.100
But you still see a circle,
even though the activation,

00:21:29.100 --> 00:21:32.910
in terms of the topography,
is nothing like a circle.

00:21:32.910 --> 00:21:40.300
So that indeed created a
much, much greater degree

00:21:40.300 --> 00:21:43.270
of skepticism
among investigators

00:21:43.270 --> 00:21:46.220
to try to understand
how we process shape.

00:21:47.546 --> 00:21:49.790
Now let me make one
other point here,

00:21:49.790 --> 00:21:52.060
which is a wonderful
story, which

00:21:52.060 --> 00:21:55.320
I think will be good
for you to remember.

00:21:55.320 --> 00:21:57.530
That's called the
Giotto story, which

00:21:57.530 --> 00:21:59.850
says that when Pope
Benedict, that was

00:21:59.850 --> 00:22:05.610
in the 12th century,
or the 13th century,

00:22:05.610 --> 00:22:09.620
he set out to have the walls
of the great cathedral of Saint

00:22:09.620 --> 00:22:13.740
Peter in Rome redecorated.

00:22:13.740 --> 00:22:17.510
And so he sent out a
bunch of messengers

00:22:17.510 --> 00:22:21.570
to various artists
in Italy and asked

00:22:21.570 --> 00:22:24.560
them to provide some
of their best work

00:22:24.560 --> 00:22:26.530
so he could evaluate
it and could

00:22:26.530 --> 00:22:30.005
pick one guy to actually
do the redecoration.

00:22:31.010 --> 00:22:37.520
Well, one of these messengers
went to Ambrogio Bondone Giotto

00:22:37.520 --> 00:22:40.290
and asked him, he was
a well known artist,

00:22:40.290 --> 00:22:44.830
and asked him to provide
a painting of his,

00:22:44.830 --> 00:22:46.270
a drawing of his.

00:22:46.270 --> 00:22:49.210
And Giotto said,
oh, my goodness.

00:22:49.210 --> 00:22:50.760
I just don't have
anything around.

00:22:50.760 --> 00:22:52.420
But I tell you what I'll do.

00:22:52.420 --> 00:22:57.180
He took out a red pen and
drew a perfect circle, OK.

00:22:57.180 --> 00:23:01.370
And so the messenger
took this to the pope.

00:23:01.370 --> 00:23:02.700
And the pope said, my god.

00:23:02.700 --> 00:23:04.700
I can't believe how
incredible this is.

00:23:04.700 --> 00:23:09.610
And so Giotto got the
job of redecorating

00:23:09.610 --> 00:23:13.630
the cathedral of Saint Peter.

00:23:13.630 --> 00:23:18.820
To this day, there is
this expression in Italy,

00:23:18.820 --> 00:23:25.390
in Tuscany in Italy, which
says the round O of Giotto, OK.

00:23:25.390 --> 00:23:27.810
So this is the
round O of Giotto,

00:23:27.810 --> 00:23:32.850
which somehow, in a sense,
denotes perfection, perfection

00:23:32.850 --> 00:23:38.580
in sight and in perfection
in your ability of execution

00:23:38.580 --> 00:23:40.890
in terms of a
drawing, for example.

00:23:40.890 --> 00:23:44.350
All right, now to highlight
this even further,

00:23:44.350 --> 00:23:46.470
let me point out
this to you here.

00:23:46.470 --> 00:23:53.040
What we have here is a bunch of
imperfect circles, one of which

00:23:53.040 --> 00:23:54.810
is perfect.

00:23:54.810 --> 00:23:56.810
So if you keep
looking around, you

00:23:56.810 --> 00:23:58.920
should be able to
spot which one it is.

00:23:58.920 --> 00:24:02.170
And you should tell me what
letter denotes that circle.

00:24:02.170 --> 00:24:03.420
Which one is a perfect circle?

00:24:06.000 --> 00:24:06.790
AUDIENCE: C.

00:24:06.790 --> 00:24:08.510
PROFESSOR: Very good, all right.

00:24:08.510 --> 00:24:10.370
So we are incredibly good.

00:24:10.370 --> 00:24:13.320
There's a slight difference
here, OK, or even slight

00:24:13.320 --> 00:24:14.280
difference here.

00:24:14.280 --> 00:24:17.060
And yet, we can see this
very slight difference.

00:24:18.330 --> 00:24:20.520
And we can tell what
a perfect circle is.

00:24:20.520 --> 00:24:24.890
I mean, that's incredible
given how the impressions are

00:24:24.890 --> 00:24:29.380
made by those circles
on the visual cortex.

00:24:29.380 --> 00:24:31.685
So that is an
incredible puzzle of how

00:24:31.685 --> 00:24:33.570
we are capable of doing this.

00:24:33.570 --> 00:24:35.370
And I'm afraid,
even to this day,

00:24:35.370 --> 00:24:39.110
we don't have a really good
answer of how this happens.

00:24:39.110 --> 00:24:50.340
OK, now the third theory
that has become actually

00:24:50.340 --> 00:24:53.940
probably right now, one of
the most successful ones,

00:24:53.940 --> 00:24:59.540
it claims that you
analyze the visual scene

00:24:59.540 --> 00:25:04.950
by taking into account the
spatial frequencies that

00:25:04.950 --> 00:25:08.590
are impinging on the retina, OK.

00:25:08.590 --> 00:25:11.470
This was created by Fergus
Campbell and John Robson,

00:25:11.470 --> 00:25:12.950
very influential.

00:25:12.950 --> 00:25:17.230
And they pointed out, first of
all, that a very interesting

00:25:17.230 --> 00:25:19.880
finding, which I think
I've mentioned once

00:25:19.880 --> 00:25:23.590
before, that if you vary the
spatial frequency [? both, ?]

00:25:23.590 --> 00:25:27.790
as well as the contrast, we
have this sensitivity function

00:25:27.790 --> 00:25:28.700
like this.

00:25:28.700 --> 00:25:30.990
I did show you a picture
of it the last time.

00:25:32.370 --> 00:25:35.630
And then, furthermore,
what they had shown

00:25:35.630 --> 00:25:41.660
is that you can create all
kinds of complex precepts

00:25:41.660 --> 00:25:44.630
by varying the gratings.

00:25:44.630 --> 00:25:47.440
Make them simple gratings,
compound gratings,

00:25:47.440 --> 00:25:51.110
and compound gratings
with much lower contrast.

00:25:51.110 --> 00:25:54.194
And this is simple different
spatial frequencies.

00:25:54.194 --> 00:25:54.985
These are compound.

00:25:56.140 --> 00:25:59.390
And these, as I've said, are
lower spatial frequencies.

00:25:59.390 --> 00:26:02.190
So then if you again
squint, then you

00:26:02.190 --> 00:26:03.610
will see something
much smoother.

00:26:04.790 --> 00:26:09.260
So they actually carried out a
detailed mathematical analysis

00:26:09.260 --> 00:26:11.480
using Fourier analysis.

00:26:11.480 --> 00:26:14.300
And what they did
was quite remarkable.

00:26:14.300 --> 00:26:17.820
They would down break
down a visual scene,

00:26:17.820 --> 00:26:23.270
like a photograph of New
York with all the skylights,

00:26:23.270 --> 00:26:25.580
OK, skyscrapers.

00:26:25.580 --> 00:26:30.850
And then they would convert
that using Fourier analysis.

00:26:30.850 --> 00:26:33.860
And they could recreate
the visual scene

00:26:33.860 --> 00:26:36.955
with a high degree of
accuracy using that procedure.

00:26:38.150 --> 00:26:42.810
Now if indeed the
visual system uses this,

00:26:42.810 --> 00:26:46.390
you have a number of basic
logical requirements.

00:26:46.390 --> 00:26:50.340
And those basic logical,
let me come back to that,

00:26:50.340 --> 00:26:52.890
the basic logical
requirements are

00:26:52.890 --> 00:26:57.220
that you need spatial
frequency analysis.

00:26:57.220 --> 00:27:00.770
And I've shown you that already
when we talked about V1,

00:27:00.770 --> 00:27:05.680
that neurons there are
spatial frequency selective.

00:27:05.680 --> 00:27:09.000
Secondly, that there
are contrast selective,

00:27:09.000 --> 00:27:10.300
which you know already.

00:27:10.300 --> 00:27:13.270
And of course, the
orientation selective,

00:27:13.270 --> 00:27:16.830
and they can tell
you about phase.

00:27:16.830 --> 00:27:19.410
As long as you have
these four attributes,

00:27:19.410 --> 00:27:22.840
you can perform a
detailed Fourier analysis

00:27:22.840 --> 00:27:25.170
to reconstruct the visual scene.

00:27:25.170 --> 00:27:28.270
So now to stress
this even further,

00:27:28.270 --> 00:27:32.270
they did a series of
experiments, in which they

00:27:32.270 --> 00:27:35.420
asked a question,
is it true that you

00:27:35.420 --> 00:27:37.710
have a particular spatial
frequency analysis,

00:27:37.710 --> 00:27:39.570
that you can manipulate that?

00:27:39.570 --> 00:27:42.490
And so they did an
experiment, which

00:27:42.490 --> 00:27:46.130
called a frequency-specific
adaptation experiment.

00:27:46.130 --> 00:27:49.530
They would present to
a subject this display

00:27:49.530 --> 00:27:52.840
and have the subject look at
this for a couple of minutes

00:27:52.840 --> 00:27:54.670
without having to fixate.

00:27:54.670 --> 00:27:56.760
And then they would
look at each of those.

00:27:56.760 --> 00:28:00.150
And they found that this, which
is the same spatial frequency,

00:28:00.150 --> 00:28:03.890
they had difficulty seeing
because of this adaptation.

00:28:03.890 --> 00:28:07.080
And so then they did a
series of careful studies

00:28:07.080 --> 00:28:09.420
and carried out this
analysis and showed

00:28:09.420 --> 00:28:13.250
that you could get any
kind of spatial frequency

00:28:13.250 --> 00:28:16.240
to lose your sensitivity
for it if you

00:28:16.240 --> 00:28:18.170
had been pre-exposed to it.

00:28:18.170 --> 00:28:19.860
So that's what that looked like.

00:28:19.860 --> 00:28:22.070
And by doing this
systematically,

00:28:22.070 --> 00:28:24.880
they came up with
the idea that what

00:28:24.880 --> 00:28:31.080
you have in the visual cortex
is a series of channels

00:28:31.080 --> 00:28:33.765
that are spatial
frequency-selective.

00:28:34.850 --> 00:28:37.610
And I showed you
we talked about V1,

00:28:37.610 --> 00:28:41.760
that indeed, there are neurons
there that are selected

00:28:41.760 --> 00:28:43.640
to particular
spatial frequencies.

00:28:43.640 --> 00:28:47.510
And they proposed that you have
a series of channels like this,

00:28:47.510 --> 00:28:51.550
OK, that peak at different
spatial frequencies.

00:28:52.740 --> 00:28:55.160
And by activating
them selectively,

00:28:55.160 --> 00:28:57.830
you can reconstruct
virtually anything out

00:28:57.830 --> 00:29:00.750
in the visual scene
using Fourier analysis.

00:29:00.750 --> 00:29:11.080
Now OK, I think that then is
the essence of that theory.

00:29:11.080 --> 00:29:14.550
And I can tell you that some
people avidly believe in it.

00:29:14.550 --> 00:29:17.790
And there are some people
who are highly skeptical.

00:29:17.790 --> 00:29:20.320
I'm not sure where I stand
at this stage about that.

00:29:24.720 --> 00:29:30.330
But now, people began
to study our shape,

00:29:30.330 --> 00:29:36.480
the ability to see shapes by
recording various visual areas.

00:29:36.480 --> 00:29:40.450
And I want to tell you next
about some studies that

00:29:40.450 --> 00:29:43.450
had been done primarily
in Japan looking

00:29:43.450 --> 00:29:47.900
at inferotemporal cortex,
which is [INAUDIBLE] already

00:29:47.900 --> 00:29:52.680
mentioned that to be involved
in the analysis of shapes

00:29:52.680 --> 00:29:57.430
and in particular, in the
analysis of faces as well.

00:29:57.430 --> 00:30:01.150
So what these
investigators did is

00:30:01.150 --> 00:30:03.910
they would record to
individual neurons

00:30:03.910 --> 00:30:07.735
in inferotemporal cortex.

00:30:09.030 --> 00:30:13.730
And when they did that, they
would present various stimuli

00:30:13.730 --> 00:30:15.135
to see how those
cells responded.

00:30:16.590 --> 00:30:19.630
And they found, they
claimed to find,

00:30:19.630 --> 00:30:22.750
that there was some
incredible specificity

00:30:22.750 --> 00:30:26.370
in inferotemporal
cortex for shapes.

00:30:26.370 --> 00:30:29.120
And so what they did,
here's an example.

00:30:29.120 --> 00:30:32.430
Here, we have the neurons'
responses, histograms.

00:30:32.430 --> 00:30:35.040
And on top, above it, we
have the particular shape

00:30:35.040 --> 00:30:37.000
that was presented repeatedly.

00:30:37.000 --> 00:30:40.940
So this particular cell
responded vigorously to this,

00:30:40.940 --> 00:30:44.370
but very poorly to that,
and so on down the line.

00:30:44.370 --> 00:30:46.090
But you can see
that it responded

00:30:46.090 --> 00:30:48.370
to several different shapes,
quite well to this one,

00:30:48.370 --> 00:30:52.480
reasonably well to that one,
so a whole range of them.

00:30:53.490 --> 00:30:57.650
So it wasn't like this
particular neuron responded

00:30:57.650 --> 00:31:00.340
only to one particular shape.

00:31:00.340 --> 00:31:02.670
But that idea that
you have neurons

00:31:02.670 --> 00:31:05.980
which are specific
for certain shapes

00:31:05.980 --> 00:31:12.990
did take on a lot of attraction
on part of investigators.

00:31:12.990 --> 00:31:15.540
And some of them
indeed thought that you

00:31:15.540 --> 00:31:20.180
have these neurons
which are selective

00:31:20.180 --> 00:31:23.050
to individual elements
in the visual scene.

00:31:24.490 --> 00:31:29.790
And those subsequently
the critics refer to

00:31:29.790 --> 00:31:33.050
as your having
grandmother cells.

00:31:33.050 --> 00:31:35.100
Somewhere in the
brain there's a cell

00:31:35.100 --> 00:31:37.900
that represents your
grandmother, all right.

00:31:37.900 --> 00:31:41.530
Now that idea was
disabuse subsequently.

00:31:41.530 --> 00:31:46.620
But it took very stronghold
in many investigators' minds.

00:31:46.620 --> 00:31:48.600
And here's another
example of yet

00:31:48.600 --> 00:31:51.260
another inferotemporal
neurons, in this case again

00:31:51.260 --> 00:31:55.450
for various shapes, showing
that this shape was,

00:31:55.450 --> 00:31:58.000
elicited a lot of responses,
as well as did this.

00:31:58.000 --> 00:32:00.950
The rest of them didn't
respond, didn't elicit as much

00:32:00.950 --> 00:32:02.370
of a response.

00:32:02.370 --> 00:32:05.760
So these kinds of
experiments then,

00:32:05.760 --> 00:32:06.843
they tried to systematize.

00:32:07.860 --> 00:32:12.810
And they came up with an idea
which, at least to my mind,

00:32:12.810 --> 00:32:16.070
borders on the absurd,
which is shown here.

00:32:16.070 --> 00:32:18.750
Here is a section of
inferotemporal cortex.

00:32:18.750 --> 00:32:21.380
And they argue that
they are columns there,

00:32:21.380 --> 00:32:25.610
and that these columns
represent different percepts.

00:32:25.610 --> 00:32:27.780
So here we have a
bunch of percepts

00:32:27.780 --> 00:32:28.970
that process the monkey.

00:32:28.970 --> 00:32:33.470
This is a monkey, of course,
that process monkey faces.

00:32:33.470 --> 00:32:35.070
And by inference,
therefore, there

00:32:35.070 --> 00:32:38.330
must be some areas in
inferotemporal cortex

00:32:38.330 --> 00:32:42.260
that process human
faces in humans.

00:32:42.260 --> 00:32:44.790
And then others process
different aspects

00:32:44.790 --> 00:32:45.770
of the visual scene.

00:32:46.970 --> 00:32:51.430
Now the big problem, technical
problem, with this approach

00:32:51.430 --> 00:32:55.530
is that when you record
from individual neurons,

00:32:55.530 --> 00:32:57.780
all right, typically
in these experiments,

00:32:57.780 --> 00:33:01.790
you can study a single neuron
for a fairly limited time,

00:33:01.790 --> 00:33:06.890
not like for months on end, just
maybe a few hours or something.

00:33:06.890 --> 00:33:09.150
And so because of
that, you can only

00:33:09.150 --> 00:33:12.890
present a limited number
of visual stimuli.

00:33:12.890 --> 00:33:16.510
Now there are millions of
visual stimuli out there.

00:33:16.510 --> 00:33:19.850
And so to really establish how
specific this particular neuron

00:33:19.850 --> 00:33:22.920
is, they say well, these are
the only shapes it's showing us.

00:33:22.920 --> 00:33:28.004
What if you use the
cross, or who knows,

00:33:28.004 --> 00:33:29.420
many, many other
things, something

00:33:29.420 --> 00:33:30.990
that is three dimensional?

00:33:30.990 --> 00:33:32.910
How would these cells respond?

00:33:32.910 --> 00:33:36.297
And so these cells respond
to different degrees,

00:33:36.297 --> 00:33:38.755
to hundreds and hundreds and
hundreds of different stimuli.

00:33:39.860 --> 00:33:44.440
And the real fact then is
that anytime a stimulus

00:33:44.440 --> 00:33:48.290
appears out there, you're
activating tens of thousands

00:33:48.290 --> 00:33:53.580
of neurons, maybe even
more, in the visual system.

00:33:53.580 --> 00:33:55.400
And each of those
neurons, especially

00:33:55.400 --> 00:34:00.450
in inferotemporal cortex,
responds to different degrees

00:34:00.450 --> 00:34:02.170
to the different stimuli.

00:34:02.170 --> 00:34:07.680
It is the compendium of these
many, many neurons firing

00:34:07.680 --> 00:34:10.590
into different degrees
to different stimuli

00:34:10.590 --> 00:34:14.400
that gives you sort of an
overall computational ability

00:34:14.400 --> 00:34:16.810
to say what that stimulus is.

00:34:16.810 --> 00:34:20.370
Now to be able to analyze
that, it is that complicated,

00:34:20.370 --> 00:34:22.989
that really takes
a lot of effort.

00:34:22.989 --> 00:34:25.630
Now some people are
now trying to do this.

00:34:25.630 --> 00:34:29.389
And the way you
try to do this is

00:34:29.389 --> 00:34:31.389
that you're recording
from hundreds and hundreds

00:34:31.389 --> 00:34:35.620
of neurons with
multiple electrodes,

00:34:35.620 --> 00:34:37.820
present various scenes.

00:34:37.820 --> 00:34:42.070
And you see how these neurons
respond as an aggregate,

00:34:42.070 --> 00:34:45.400
so that you can determine
whether or not there is indeed

00:34:45.400 --> 00:34:48.880
the potential for some
sort of computation

00:34:48.880 --> 00:34:52.929
that takes place in
gaining the impression

00:34:52.929 --> 00:34:56.570
of a particular individual face.

00:34:56.570 --> 00:34:59.340
Now one of the very
important facts

00:34:59.340 --> 00:35:02.900
here is, of course, that as you
look around the visual scene,

00:35:02.900 --> 00:35:04.820
let's imagine you're
looking at a face.

00:35:04.820 --> 00:35:06.392
You're looking at
a face head on.

00:35:06.392 --> 00:35:07.975
You're looking at a
face in a profile.

00:35:07.975 --> 00:35:09.764
You're looking at a face tilted.

00:35:09.764 --> 00:35:11.055
You're looking at a face close.

00:35:11.055 --> 00:35:13.200
You're looking at a face far.

00:35:13.200 --> 00:35:15.090
And it's still
all the same face.

00:35:15.090 --> 00:35:17.920
And yet the
impressions that face

00:35:17.920 --> 00:35:23.050
makes on the visual
system, in the retina,

00:35:23.050 --> 00:35:27.890
in the geniculate, in the visual
cortex, varies a great deal.

00:35:27.890 --> 00:35:31.060
And yet we can come
up with constancy,

00:35:31.060 --> 00:35:33.280
which is sort of a
higher level process.

00:35:33.280 --> 00:35:36.040
And I'll come to
that in short order.

00:35:36.040 --> 00:35:39.180
All right, so now,
therefore, we need

00:35:39.180 --> 00:35:44.000
to start to talk about what we
call intermediate level vision.

00:35:45.470 --> 00:35:47.350
What is intermediate
level vision?

00:35:47.350 --> 00:35:49.760
So far, we've talked
almost exclusively

00:35:49.760 --> 00:35:53.470
about basic visual capacities,
color, brightness, pattern,

00:35:53.470 --> 00:35:55.720
texture, motion,
depth, the very,

00:35:55.720 --> 00:35:57.410
just the very basic types.

00:35:57.410 --> 00:36:00.880
But now when we talk about
intermediate visual capacities,

00:36:00.880 --> 00:36:02.580
we talk about constancy.

00:36:02.580 --> 00:36:04.350
One example of
constancy, of course,

00:36:04.350 --> 00:36:06.590
is that the face that
you're looking at,

00:36:06.590 --> 00:36:10.010
whether it's profile, or head
on, or near, or far, it's

00:36:10.010 --> 00:36:11.140
still the same face.

00:36:11.140 --> 00:36:13.810
So we get constancy out of it.

00:36:13.810 --> 00:36:16.610
Then there's an
important necessity

00:36:16.610 --> 00:36:19.020
to be able to select
various aspects out

00:36:19.020 --> 00:36:23.270
of the visual scene, to be
able to select if you recognize

00:36:23.270 --> 00:36:28.500
things, to induce
transposition and variance,

00:36:28.500 --> 00:36:30.950
and to be able to
make comparisons,

00:36:30.950 --> 00:36:34.860
and also lastly, to be able to
say where things are in space.

00:36:34.860 --> 00:36:37.190
So those are these
intermediate capacities.

00:36:37.190 --> 00:36:40.150
And we'll talk a little
bit about them next.

00:36:40.150 --> 00:36:44.650
All right, so here's an
example of constancy.

00:36:44.650 --> 00:36:48.715
What we have here
is a bunch of words

00:36:48.715 --> 00:36:52.360
for doubt in different
sizes, and orientations,

00:36:52.360 --> 00:36:56.020
and some handwritten, and so on.

00:36:56.020 --> 00:36:58.260
And yet all of them say
the same thing, doubt.

00:36:58.260 --> 00:37:00.210
We extract that, OK.

00:37:00.210 --> 00:37:04.720
Now to make this
even more difficult,

00:37:04.720 --> 00:37:08.380
I'm going to tell you that
there's one of these words here

00:37:08.380 --> 00:37:10.780
which is not doubt
and see who can

00:37:10.780 --> 00:37:12.610
find the word that is not doubt.

00:37:16.380 --> 00:37:18.840
Everybody find it yet?

00:37:18.840 --> 00:37:24.250
OK, right there, not
doubt but doubts.

00:37:24.250 --> 00:37:27.570
And so we are able to
extract the difference

00:37:27.570 --> 00:37:29.750
in this kind of
visual scene, even

00:37:29.750 --> 00:37:31.810
though it is incredibly subtle.

00:37:31.810 --> 00:37:35.680
And yet, we are also able
to say that this doubt,

00:37:35.680 --> 00:37:38.760
and this doubt, and this
doubt are all the same,

00:37:38.760 --> 00:37:42.930
even though they're different
size or different in print.

00:37:44.890 --> 00:37:48.220
We can extract from
that the common element.

00:37:48.220 --> 00:37:50.160
So this is an
incredible capacity

00:37:50.160 --> 00:37:51.440
on part of the visual system.

00:37:52.500 --> 00:37:57.570
And of course, the big question
comes up, how is this achieved?

00:37:57.570 --> 00:38:00.720
And at this stage, we only
have very preliminary answers

00:38:00.720 --> 00:38:01.640
to that.

00:38:01.640 --> 00:38:06.630
OK, so now I want to show you a
