00:42:21.230 --> 00:42:23.300
But he's such a
remarkable artist

00:42:23.300 --> 00:42:27.900
that he could create Voltaire
by playing around with this, OK.

00:42:29.990 --> 00:42:33.035
So let me go back to
the display again.

00:42:46.900 --> 00:42:48.920
OK, so this is Salvador Dali.

00:42:50.200 --> 00:42:53.720
And certainly, it's an
artist who is remarkable.

00:42:53.720 --> 00:42:56.930
He has many paintings
in which this kind

00:42:56.930 --> 00:43:01.590
of a double confusing thing,
playing on your ability to see.

00:43:01.590 --> 00:43:04.720
So because of that,
for people like me

00:43:04.720 --> 00:43:06.890
who's interested in
how we see things,

00:43:06.890 --> 00:43:09.830
certainly I'm very
intrigued by his artwork.

00:43:09.830 --> 00:43:14.790
And you may enjoy looking
that up again on the internet.

00:43:14.790 --> 00:43:21.180
OK, so now I'm going to tell you
yet another interesting aspect

00:43:21.180 --> 00:43:23.856
of art involved in this.

00:43:23.856 --> 00:43:30.530
And this one has to do with a
book, a very clever book that

00:43:30.530 --> 00:43:33.460
was written by David Hockney.

00:43:33.460 --> 00:43:35.380
Has anybody ever heard of him?

00:43:36.720 --> 00:43:38.810
I'm not surprised since
he's not that well known.

00:43:39.960 --> 00:43:43.105
But the book he wrote is
called Secret Knowledge.

00:43:44.196 --> 00:43:46.290
Now what was that all about?

00:43:46.290 --> 00:43:55.400
Well, he analyzed how artists
created paintings way,

00:43:55.400 --> 00:43:59.380
way, way back when and
in subsequent years

00:43:59.380 --> 00:44:01.730
up to the present.

00:44:01.730 --> 00:44:04.590
And now I'm going to show
you some of his pictures

00:44:04.590 --> 00:44:07.040
and give you a sense of
what this is all about.

00:44:07.040 --> 00:44:15.490
Here is a picture, OK, by
Masolino da Panicale in 1425.

00:44:15.490 --> 00:44:18.530
This was a typical kind
of picture back then.

00:44:18.530 --> 00:44:20.780
Artists had a very
poor sense of how

00:44:20.780 --> 00:44:24.930
to create depth
perception in a painting.

00:44:26.440 --> 00:44:28.840
That was before they came
up with vanishing point.

00:44:30.210 --> 00:44:35.430
And so this kind of looks flat
and fairly expressionless.

00:44:36.690 --> 00:44:39.220
This was in 1425.

00:44:39.220 --> 00:44:44.440
And then Hockney noticed
that just five years later,

00:44:44.440 --> 00:44:50.290
another artist came
up with a picture,

00:44:50.290 --> 00:44:53.960
just five years later, that
looks almost like a photograph.

00:44:55.370 --> 00:44:57.555
And he said, what on
earth has happened?

00:44:58.940 --> 00:45:01.610
And that's why the book is
called the Secret Knowledge.

00:45:01.610 --> 00:45:02.560
So what happened?

00:45:02.560 --> 00:45:03.200
Anybody know?

00:45:05.657 --> 00:45:06.240
Ah, all right.

00:45:06.240 --> 00:45:07.739
Well, let me tell
you what happened.

00:45:07.739 --> 00:45:16.530
What happened is that at
that time, in the 1400s,

00:45:16.530 --> 00:45:19.800
they came up with the lens, OK.

00:45:21.350 --> 00:45:27.385
And so they created a device
called the camera obscura.

00:45:28.710 --> 00:45:30.670
Does anybody know what
the camera obscura is?

00:45:32.140 --> 00:45:39.520
It's essentially very
similar to a camera, OK.

00:45:40.550 --> 00:45:41.940
So here we have it.

00:45:41.940 --> 00:45:43.120
Here's a camera obscura.

00:45:44.380 --> 00:45:47.240
And what they did,
these artists,

00:45:47.240 --> 00:45:49.580
they would create a building.

00:45:49.580 --> 00:45:51.400
So it will be dark inside.

00:45:51.400 --> 00:45:53.280
And then they would
put the lens here.

00:45:53.280 --> 00:45:55.110
And they would put
some object out here

00:45:55.110 --> 00:45:59.390
that they wanted to
make a painting of.

00:45:59.390 --> 00:46:04.670
And that would be reflected
onto a piece of canvas here.

00:46:04.670 --> 00:46:06.890
Of course, it would
be upside down, right?

00:46:06.890 --> 00:46:09.050
And then they would paint it.

00:46:09.050 --> 00:46:12.980
And so once it was painted,
they could turn it around

00:46:12.980 --> 00:46:16.910
and finish it and sell it.

00:46:16.910 --> 00:46:20.040
Now, the reason they did this,
the prime reason they did this,

00:46:20.040 --> 00:46:23.470
is because it was much
much, much quicker

00:46:23.470 --> 00:46:25.700
to create a portrait,
for example,

00:46:25.700 --> 00:46:29.880
by using this procedure than
to actually look at a person

00:46:29.880 --> 00:46:35.620
and paint them on the
canvas while looking at it.

00:46:35.620 --> 00:46:36.120
OK.

00:46:37.230 --> 00:46:38.720
So that was done.

00:46:38.720 --> 00:46:41.270
And of course, this was
sort of a no, no thing.

00:46:41.270 --> 00:46:44.850
And because of that,
it was kept secret.

00:46:44.850 --> 00:46:47.780
All these artists who did this,
and some very famous artists

00:46:47.780 --> 00:46:57.540
did so, were very careful
never to disclose to the public

00:46:57.540 --> 00:46:58.950
that they did this
kind of thing.

00:46:58.950 --> 00:47:02.780
Because it was conceived to be
kind of a cheating thing, OK.

00:47:02.780 --> 00:47:08.390
So what happened then was
that all these paintings were

00:47:08.390 --> 00:47:09.170
created.

00:47:09.170 --> 00:47:13.100
And here's an example
by van Eyck in 1436.

00:47:13.100 --> 00:47:15.430
Again, this looks much
like a photograph.

00:47:15.430 --> 00:47:18.210
But some other thing
is a bit distorted.

00:47:18.210 --> 00:47:24.050
So Hockney undertook a
careful, detailed analysis

00:47:24.050 --> 00:47:26.810
of how we could tell
whether a painting was

00:47:26.810 --> 00:47:31.380
a real painting or one that
used the camera obscura method.

00:47:31.380 --> 00:47:33.220
And that's also a real
painting in a sense,

00:47:33.220 --> 00:47:37.270
but a painting using the
camera obscura method.

00:47:37.270 --> 00:47:39.580
And he came up with
a series of criteria

00:47:39.580 --> 00:47:40.850
which are listed in the book.

00:47:40.850 --> 00:47:43.140
But I'm only going to
deal with one of them.

00:47:43.140 --> 00:47:44.535
OK, so here is an example.

00:47:47.050 --> 00:47:49.510
This is in 1597.

00:47:49.510 --> 00:47:51.473
This is by Caravaggio, OK.

00:47:52.830 --> 00:47:54.540
And what is notable
about this person?

00:47:59.940 --> 00:48:03.580
Well, to Hockney,
what was notable

00:48:03.580 --> 00:48:05.820
is that this person
is holding the wine

00:48:05.820 --> 00:48:07.684
glass in his left hand.

00:48:07.684 --> 00:48:08.184
Yeah?

00:48:09.440 --> 00:48:11.000
And he said, huh.

00:48:11.000 --> 00:48:12.069
That's curious.

00:48:12.069 --> 00:48:14.360
And then he looked at a whole
bunch of other paintings.

00:48:14.360 --> 00:48:15.810
And he had one in
which there were

00:48:15.810 --> 00:48:19.090
three people on the painting.

00:48:19.090 --> 00:48:21.170
And all three of them
were left handed.

00:48:21.170 --> 00:48:22.350
Yeah.

00:48:22.350 --> 00:48:24.760
And he said, my god,
that is really curious.

00:48:24.760 --> 00:48:26.200
And he said, well,
let me analyze

00:48:26.200 --> 00:48:30.480
what happens when you
do this kind of stuff

00:48:30.480 --> 00:48:33.000
with the camera obscura method.

00:48:33.000 --> 00:48:34.780
So here's the example of this.

00:48:34.780 --> 00:48:38.350
This is the original
image, he claims,

00:48:38.350 --> 00:48:41.630
meaning the person is right
handed, is not left handed.

00:48:41.630 --> 00:48:45.470
Then you put this
person through the lens

00:48:45.470 --> 00:48:49.940
and put him up here
upside down like that, OK.

00:48:49.940 --> 00:48:53.520
He's painted on the
canvas like that.

00:48:53.520 --> 00:48:58.910
And then what you do is you
rotate this 180 degrees.

00:48:58.910 --> 00:49:00.930
And when you do
that, lo and behold,

00:49:00.930 --> 00:49:02.660
the person becomes left hand.

00:49:02.660 --> 00:49:05.110
And to make this clear,
I added the F here.

00:49:05.110 --> 00:49:07.360
So this is a normal
F. This is what

00:49:07.360 --> 00:49:12.130
is projected onto the canvas.

00:49:12.130 --> 00:49:14.370
And this is when you
rotate it 180 degrees.

00:49:15.540 --> 00:49:19.370
So you reverse the left
according to Hockney,

00:49:19.370 --> 00:49:22.130
reverse the image.

00:49:22.130 --> 00:49:29.300
And so it was a dead giveaway
that most of the people who

00:49:29.300 --> 00:49:33.360
appeared left handed in his
paintings, in these paintings,

00:49:33.360 --> 00:49:34.910
I should say, not
just Caravaggio,

00:49:34.910 --> 00:49:39.910
but several other people,
used the camera obscura method

00:49:39.910 --> 00:49:42.510
for creating the painting.

00:49:42.510 --> 00:49:46.680
All right, so that
is the process.

00:49:46.680 --> 00:49:50.250
And then I want to show you
one more example of this.

00:49:50.250 --> 00:49:53.820
OK, this is a very famous
painting also, all right.

00:49:55.320 --> 00:50:00.576
This is the so-called marriage
of Giovanni Arnolfini.

00:50:03.070 --> 00:50:08.370
And this by van Eyck, again
1493, way, way, way, way, way,

00:50:08.370 --> 00:50:09.280
way back then.

00:50:09.280 --> 00:50:11.656
Now this is a famous painting.

00:50:11.656 --> 00:50:13.030
Now there's one
interesting thing

00:50:13.030 --> 00:50:14.080
first of all I
want to point out.

00:50:14.080 --> 00:50:15.100
You see this here?

00:50:16.670 --> 00:50:19.080
That's proof that
in those days they

00:50:19.080 --> 00:50:22.150
had come up with the lens, yeah.

00:50:24.700 --> 00:50:28.100
Now what is wrong
with this picture?

00:50:32.100 --> 00:50:35.700
This guy who is about
to marry this woman

00:50:35.700 --> 00:50:38.380
is holding her
with his left hand.

00:50:39.114 --> 00:50:40.280
I mean, that's unacceptable.

00:50:41.840 --> 00:50:45.010
You're supposed to hold it
with the right hand, yeah.

00:50:45.010 --> 00:50:47.400
Now the reason he's holding
it with the left hand

00:50:47.400 --> 00:50:54.200
is because the artist, van
Eyck, used the camera, according

00:50:54.200 --> 00:51:01.460
to Hockney, used the camera
obscura method to take this,

00:51:01.460 --> 00:51:03.710
to paint this picture, OK.

00:51:03.710 --> 00:51:07.420
And then he rotated
180 degrees and became,

00:51:07.420 --> 00:51:08.965
he became left
handed as a result.

00:51:11.690 --> 00:51:16.040
Now if instead of having
done that, you would go back,

00:51:16.040 --> 00:51:17.530
you don't have to go back.

00:51:18.865 --> 00:51:21.300
Go back to here, and
let's go back to this.

00:51:21.300 --> 00:51:28.750
If you take this guy here
and you create the picture.

00:51:28.750 --> 00:51:32.190
But then instead of rotating
it, if you could flip it,

00:51:32.190 --> 00:51:35.860
then you would, he will
remain right handed.

00:51:35.860 --> 00:51:39.380
But of course, we can't do
that because it's on a canvas.

00:51:39.380 --> 00:51:40.505
It's not on a transparency.

00:51:42.240 --> 00:51:48.780
So that then is the
interesting story of artwork

00:51:48.780 --> 00:51:51.820
that was created using
the camera obscura

00:51:51.820 --> 00:51:55.790
system that further
the highlights

00:51:55.790 --> 00:52:03.310
the amazing interestingly
complicated manner

00:52:03.310 --> 00:52:06.620
in which we can analyze the
visual scene for shapes.

00:52:07.690 --> 00:52:14.100
All right, now another factor
that is in a similar vein

00:52:14.100 --> 00:52:17.250
has to do with the
recognition of faces.

00:52:17.250 --> 00:52:20.360
Lots of experiments have
been done, including several

00:52:20.360 --> 00:52:24.090
in our department here,
that has recognized

00:52:24.090 --> 00:52:32.720
that, unfortunate use of
terms, recognition, recognize,

00:52:32.720 --> 00:52:36.940
became aware of the fact that
facial recognition depends

00:52:36.940 --> 00:52:40.720
very heavily on seeing
faces right side up.

00:52:40.720 --> 00:52:46.350
When faces are upside down,
you have great difficulty

00:52:46.350 --> 00:52:48.720
telling who is who, OK.

00:52:48.720 --> 00:52:50.080
So let's do that.

00:52:50.080 --> 00:52:51.760
Here are a bunch of faces.

00:52:51.760 --> 00:52:55.000
And I bet you can you
can tell this one, right?

00:52:55.000 --> 00:52:55.540
Who is it?

00:52:57.250 --> 00:52:58.150
And who is this?

00:52:59.440 --> 00:53:00.000
Very good.

00:53:01.840 --> 00:53:03.920
And those two you don't know.

00:53:03.920 --> 00:53:06.770
The problem is that I am
going to flip this over now.

00:53:06.770 --> 00:53:08.780
And you still don't
know who those two are.

00:53:13.110 --> 00:53:16.290
OK, so this one
is Norbert Wiener.

00:53:16.290 --> 00:53:18.185
Now all of you know
about Norbert Wiener.

00:53:18.185 --> 00:53:20.590
He is one of the great
geniuses of our time.

00:53:20.590 --> 00:53:22.415
He came up with
the digital code.

00:53:23.600 --> 00:53:27.030
He used to be a
professor at MIT.

00:53:27.030 --> 00:53:29.340
And this here is Chuck Vest.

00:53:29.340 --> 00:53:31.240
Anybody recognize him?

00:53:32.490 --> 00:53:36.650
Chuck Vest was a
president of MIT for what?

00:53:36.650 --> 00:53:39.620
For eight years, I believe,
maybe more, 12 years?

00:53:39.620 --> 00:53:40.120
I forget.

00:53:42.200 --> 00:53:47.740
And he has sunk into
obscurity, even though he

00:53:47.740 --> 00:53:50.000
was incredibly visible
for many, many years.

00:53:50.000 --> 00:53:53.970
If I had shown this to you
say eight or 10 years ago,

00:53:53.970 --> 00:53:55.980
you would immediately
recognize him.

00:53:55.980 --> 00:53:59.470
Because he, at that time,
was a president at MIT.

00:54:00.870 --> 00:54:03.890
So that then is an
interesting fact

00:54:03.890 --> 00:54:08.660
that even though we are capable
of using intermediate level

00:54:08.660 --> 00:54:12.250
vision in a very
sophisticated way,

00:54:12.250 --> 00:54:16.430
it does not seem to work that
well for upside down faces.

00:54:18.210 --> 00:54:20.620
You guys did pretty
good with those.

00:54:20.620 --> 00:54:22.290
But it takes a while.

00:54:22.290 --> 00:54:27.290
If I had flashed that
on in a tachistoscope,

00:54:27.290 --> 00:54:31.260
you wouldn't have had a vague
idea of who those people were.

00:54:31.260 --> 00:54:33.650
But once it's on for a while
and you can analyze it,

00:54:33.650 --> 00:54:38.780
you can eventually tell
even an upside down face.

00:54:38.780 --> 00:54:47.700
OK, now in the same vein
as we are talking about,

00:54:47.700 --> 00:54:57.680
our ability to process shapes
based on contours and whatnot,

00:54:57.680 --> 00:55:01.330
one of the interesting set of
experiments people had done

00:55:01.330 --> 00:55:05.070
is to look at what is
called subjective contours.

00:55:05.070 --> 00:55:07.690
And so let me give you a
couple of examples of that.

00:55:07.690 --> 00:55:09.160
Here's an example.

00:55:09.160 --> 00:55:11.520
Almost instantly, here
you can see a disk.

00:55:11.520 --> 00:55:15.430
And here you can
see a square rotated

00:55:15.430 --> 00:55:18.980
45 degrees, a
diamond if you will.

00:55:20.140 --> 00:55:22.290
But if you analyze
this carefully,

00:55:22.290 --> 00:55:27.150
you can see that about
80% of this border

00:55:27.150 --> 00:55:28.940
here is not a border.

00:55:28.940 --> 00:55:30.270
There's no border here.

00:55:30.270 --> 00:55:32.830
There's no border here,
here, here, here, here.

00:55:32.830 --> 00:55:34.770
And yet we can see a square.

00:55:34.770 --> 00:55:39.350
So there's some strange ability
in part of the visual system

00:55:39.350 --> 00:55:43.510
to complete inferred borders.

00:55:43.510 --> 00:55:45.950
All right, I'll come back
to that in just a minute.

00:55:45.950 --> 00:55:49.240
Now another example
of this is shown here.

00:55:50.740 --> 00:55:53.040
Can you make out
what it says here?

00:55:54.024 --> 00:55:56.190
If you look a little bit,
you should be able to see.

00:55:56.190 --> 00:55:57.760
What is it?

00:55:57.760 --> 00:55:59.000
Visual system, very good.

00:55:59.000 --> 00:56:00.730
It was difficult to see.

00:56:00.730 --> 00:56:04.020
But as soon as I
turn this into color,

00:56:04.020 --> 00:56:05.270
you have no trouble at all.

00:56:06.490 --> 00:56:09.290
And that highlights
another important reason

00:56:09.290 --> 00:56:13.610
why color vision is so
useful and has evolved.

00:56:13.610 --> 00:56:16.940
Because it enables
us to see borders,

00:56:16.940 --> 00:56:19.980
where under certain conditions
and lighting conditions,

00:56:19.980 --> 00:56:24.380
borders would not be visible
on the black and white.

00:56:24.380 --> 00:56:29.020
OK, so now that's another
interesting example,

00:56:29.020 --> 00:56:33.670
has to do with further
subjective contours.

00:56:33.670 --> 00:56:37.040
And here's an example of
one with a high contrast,

00:56:37.040 --> 00:56:39.600
where you can
readily see a cube.

00:56:39.600 --> 00:56:41.473
Does everybody see a cube there?

00:56:41.473 --> 00:56:45.130
All right, but if you look
here, it's next to impossible

00:56:45.130 --> 00:56:46.120
to see that.

00:56:46.120 --> 00:56:48.730
Because here the
stimuli are isoluminant.

00:56:50.820 --> 00:56:55.290
So here you eliminated
contrast, which

00:56:55.290 --> 00:56:57.290
is a very important
aspect of being

00:56:57.290 --> 00:57:05.380
able to analyze the visual
scene in various ways,

00:57:05.380 --> 00:57:06.680
including three dimensions.

00:57:06.680 --> 00:57:11.020
All right, so now here's a
very interesting discovery that

00:57:11.020 --> 00:57:14.200
was made by recording
an area, V2.

00:57:17.920 --> 00:57:20.730
The recordings were
then made to see

00:57:20.730 --> 00:57:25.850
whether those neurons
perceive subjective contours.

00:57:25.850 --> 00:57:27.880
So here's a receptive field.

00:57:27.880 --> 00:57:31.220
And you take this bar and move
it back and forth across it.

00:57:31.220 --> 00:57:33.670
And you can see it gives
a vigorous response.

00:57:33.670 --> 00:57:35.710
Now you do the same thing.

00:57:35.710 --> 00:57:39.760
But you don't, here you have
only a subjective contour.

00:57:39.760 --> 00:57:42.500
And then you move this
back and forth across.

00:57:42.500 --> 00:57:49.340
Somehow the information is
added up from other areas,

00:57:49.340 --> 00:57:53.940
so that this cell
responds, not that well,

00:57:53.940 --> 00:57:58.130
but responds reasonably well
to the subjective contour.

00:57:58.130 --> 00:58:02.440
So it's said that in
V2, you can carry out

00:58:02.440 --> 00:58:05.440
some of these higher
level processes that

00:58:05.440 --> 00:58:09.200
enables you to
complete figures even

00:58:09.200 --> 00:58:11.890
when they are
incomplete like that.

00:58:11.890 --> 00:58:14.290
OK, here's another
example of that.

00:58:14.290 --> 00:58:15.970
This is even more dramatic.

00:58:15.970 --> 00:58:18.600
In this case, we take this
bar back and forth across.

00:58:18.600 --> 00:58:20.959
That's a vigorous response.

00:58:20.959 --> 00:58:22.250
And then you do the same thing.

00:58:22.250 --> 00:58:27.370
You create a bar here simply
by these continuous horizontal

00:58:27.370 --> 00:58:28.420
bars.

00:58:28.420 --> 00:58:30.980
And still, the cell
responds quite well,

00:58:30.980 --> 00:58:34.090
as if it were
seeing an edge here.

00:58:34.090 --> 00:58:38.140
So we have this kind of
completion in area V2.

00:58:38.140 --> 00:58:40.290
So this is sort
of an initial hint

00:58:40.290 --> 00:58:44.650
then that already
in area V2, you

00:58:44.650 --> 00:58:50.210
begin to process
higher level events,

00:58:50.210 --> 00:58:52.830
among which is the
fact that you can

00:58:52.830 --> 00:58:54.690
complete incomplete contours.

00:58:55.780 --> 00:58:59.440
All right, so now, the next
thing we're going to turn to,

00:58:59.440 --> 00:59:01.970
we're going to ask
the question, when

00:59:01.970 --> 00:59:05.740
we deal with these
so-called intermediate level

00:59:05.740 --> 00:59:11.900
visual capacities, what
happens when you take out

00:59:11.900 --> 00:59:16.850
such areas as V4 and
MT to your ability

00:59:16.850 --> 00:59:19.710
to see these intermediate
visual capacities?

00:59:19.710 --> 00:59:21.990
So let me describe
to you some of these,

00:59:21.990 --> 00:59:25.230
how one would do
experiments like this.

00:59:25.230 --> 00:59:27.680
First of all,
monkeys are trained.

00:59:27.680 --> 00:59:30.320
This is done with monkeys, of
course, because we can't just

00:59:30.320 --> 00:59:32.900
take a human and remove V4 MT.

00:59:32.900 --> 00:59:38.820
And so what you do here is you
first present a fixation spot.

00:59:38.820 --> 00:59:43.390
Once the monkey fixates,
you present a shape,

00:59:43.390 --> 00:59:45.060
in this case a square.

00:59:45.060 --> 00:59:49.300
And then you present a whole
bunch of other ones, only one

00:59:49.300 --> 00:59:51.350
of which is the same
as the original.

00:59:51.350 --> 00:59:53.450
And the monkey has to
make a [INAUDIBLE] there

00:59:53.450 --> 00:59:54.710
to be rewarded.

00:59:54.710 --> 00:59:59.090
So he has to be able to
detect identity, which

00:59:59.090 --> 01:00:01.850
is an intermediate
visual capacity.

01:00:01.850 --> 01:00:03.850
So that's what this is like.

01:00:03.850 --> 01:00:08.180
And so then what
you can do here is

01:00:08.180 --> 01:00:10.930
to vary the amount
of information

01:00:10.930 --> 01:00:15.740
you can provide, again by
reducing the amount of contour

01:00:15.740 --> 01:00:17.650
information that
you can provide.

01:00:17.650 --> 01:00:19.120
You can do this in several ways.

01:00:21.320 --> 01:00:25.020
First of all, before we do that,
I'll come to that in a second,

01:00:25.020 --> 01:00:26.770
let's just see, how
does the monkey do

01:00:26.770 --> 01:00:30.040
when you do those very similar
shapes I just have shown you

01:00:30.040 --> 01:00:32.870
after you take out area V4?

01:00:32.870 --> 01:00:36.370
What you find here is that the
monkey initially, after you

01:00:36.370 --> 01:00:42.030
take out the area V4, can't
even do the regular task, which

01:00:42.030 --> 01:00:43.530
is this one, right?

01:00:43.530 --> 01:00:46.140
So this is identical to
this one in this case.

01:00:46.140 --> 01:00:49.540
And when you do that, he does
very poorly to begin with

01:00:49.540 --> 01:00:51.710
and then gradually,
over many, many days,

01:00:51.710 --> 01:00:53.540
improves a great deal.

01:00:53.540 --> 01:00:56.917
Then if you put a new figure
in, then it takes a while for it

01:00:56.917 --> 01:00:59.070
to learn that, all right.

01:00:59.070 --> 01:01:02.520
Now then, what you
can do, now I come

01:01:02.520 --> 01:01:06.550
to this business of
having these same figures.

01:01:06.550 --> 01:01:09.720
But you can vary
them now, so that you

01:01:09.720 --> 01:01:13.450
have to do a transposition to
do an intermediate visual task.

01:01:13.450 --> 01:01:17.760
In this case, what you do
is that you vary the size.

01:01:17.760 --> 01:01:20.200
In this case, it's
identical just like it was.

01:01:20.200 --> 01:01:23.394
In this case, you see that
this is smaller than this.

01:01:23.394 --> 01:01:25.310
But you say, oh, I have
to go find the circle.

01:01:26.530 --> 01:01:27.960
I'm not looking for identity.

01:01:27.960 --> 01:01:31.050
I'm looking for something
that's the same looking.

01:01:31.050 --> 01:01:32.680
And here we have
even bigger case.

01:01:32.680 --> 01:01:33.749
This is a triangle.

01:01:33.749 --> 01:01:35.290
And so the monkey
makes a [INAUDIBLE]

01:01:35.290 --> 01:01:36.940
to that one here to this one.

01:01:36.940 --> 01:01:40.870
So that has to do a
test position in size.

01:01:40.870 --> 01:01:43.350
Another thing you can
do that we talked about,

01:01:43.350 --> 01:01:46.060
you can vary the amount
of contour information

01:01:46.060 --> 01:01:48.480
by doing this kind of occlusion.

01:01:48.480 --> 01:01:50.130
And the degree of
occlusion you can

01:01:50.130 --> 01:01:53.530
vary by varying the spatial
frequency of the display.

01:01:53.530 --> 01:01:57.500
And lastly, you can also
decrease or increase the amount

01:01:57.500 --> 01:02:00.170
of contour information
that you provide.

01:02:00.170 --> 01:02:05.760
Now if you do with this, you get
a huge effect after V4 lesion.

01:02:07.210 --> 01:02:11.390
This was the normal condition
with the varied object size.

01:02:11.390 --> 01:02:13.040
This is the occlusion.

01:02:13.040 --> 01:02:16.530
And here is the varied
contour information.

01:02:16.530 --> 01:02:19.020
You can see that there is
quite a dramatic loss, not

01:02:19.020 --> 01:02:23.600
a total, but quite a notable
loss, in the monkey's ability

01:02:23.600 --> 01:02:25.130
to perform this task.

01:02:25.130 --> 01:02:28.010
And this is also reflected
in the huge increase

01:02:28.010 --> 01:02:32.230
in the latencies with which the
monkey can perform the task.

01:02:32.230 --> 01:02:35.720
So area V4 seems to
play an important role

01:02:35.720 --> 01:02:38.860
in these intermediate
visual capacities.

01:02:38.860 --> 01:02:42.240
And I come to some more examples
of that in just a minute.

01:02:42.240 --> 01:02:47.150
Now, yet another
important factor

01:02:47.150 --> 01:02:59.400
in analyzing the
visual scene occurs

01:02:59.400 --> 01:03:02.530
when it is our task
to find something

01:03:02.530 --> 01:03:05.540
out there that is
less noticeable.

01:03:06.780 --> 01:03:13.830
Remember, we talked a little
bit about using camouflage,

01:03:13.830 --> 01:03:18.105
in which case, you have to find
something lesser to survive.

01:03:19.300 --> 01:03:22.520
Now in this case,
what we can do here,

01:03:22.520 --> 01:03:24.740
do a similar
experiment in a monkey.

01:03:26.130 --> 01:03:28.820
On the left side,
the target, the one

01:03:28.820 --> 01:03:32.330
the monkey's supposed to select,
has a much higher contrast

01:03:32.330 --> 01:03:34.660
than the distractors.

01:03:34.660 --> 01:03:36.610
And you can vary the
degree of difference,

01:03:36.610 --> 01:03:39.760
but always the target is
brighter than the others,

01:03:39.760 --> 01:03:41.240
so that it stands out.

01:03:41.240 --> 01:03:44.740
But then, you must
be equally able,

01:03:44.740 --> 01:03:46.280
whether you're an
animal or a human,

01:03:46.280 --> 01:03:47.990
to be able to pull
out something that's

01:03:47.990 --> 01:03:50.615
lesser in the visuals field.

01:03:51.720 --> 01:03:55.120
And you have to
be able to do this

01:03:55.120 --> 01:04:02.555
if you are going to survive
in your environment.

01:04:02.555 --> 01:04:06.120
Now here then, the task is to
go to this lesser stimulus,

01:04:06.120 --> 01:04:07.780
because it's the odd stimulus.

01:04:07.780 --> 01:04:10.730
So what you're extracting
is the odd stimulus.

01:04:10.730 --> 01:04:14.270
Here it's easy to extract, and
here it's difficult to extract.

01:04:14.270 --> 01:04:21.830
And so now the question is what
happens in the visual cortex?

01:04:21.830 --> 01:04:25.230
What area plays a role in this?

01:04:25.230 --> 01:04:28.450
And so it was
discovered that area V4

01:04:28.450 --> 01:04:29.690
is very important for this.

01:04:29.690 --> 01:04:31.600
And let me explain
this to you then.

01:04:31.600 --> 01:04:36.480
You do an experiment in
which you remove area V4

01:04:36.480 --> 01:04:37.520
and see what happens.

01:04:39.740 --> 01:04:42.900
And here what we have is
when the star gets brighter,

01:04:42.900 --> 01:04:45.940
you vary the
luminance difference.

01:04:45.940 --> 01:04:48.900
And you can see there's a mild
deficit with the V4 lesion,

01:04:48.900 --> 01:04:50.980
highly significant
but still fairly mild.

01:04:50.980 --> 01:04:53.760
On the other hand, when
you make it dimmer,

01:04:53.760 --> 01:04:57.800
the monkey is practically
staying at the probability.

01:04:59.050 --> 01:05:01.190
He cannot do the task at all.

01:05:01.190 --> 01:05:04.360
So somehow, V4 plays
a very important role

01:05:04.360 --> 01:05:09.200
in being able to ferret
out some subtle things

01:05:09.200 --> 01:05:11.050
in the environment,
lesser things.

01:05:12.410 --> 01:05:15.860
All right, so this
then brings us

01:05:15.860 --> 01:05:17.970
to yet another way
of analyzing this.

01:05:17.970 --> 01:05:21.370
We can, in this case,
go to the larger target,

01:05:21.370 --> 01:05:23.250
in this case to
the smaller target.

01:05:23.250 --> 01:05:25.660
And you can recognize yourself
that this is certainly

01:05:25.660 --> 01:05:27.190
easier than that.

01:05:27.190 --> 01:05:31.820
But a normal monkey can do
both of these quite well,

01:05:31.820 --> 01:05:32.750
shown here.

01:05:32.750 --> 01:05:34.520
This is the normal
monkey's performance,

01:05:34.520 --> 01:05:37.300
the target larger, here
the target smaller.

01:05:37.300 --> 01:05:38.840
He does extremely well.

01:05:38.840 --> 01:05:41.880
But with a V4 lesion when
the target is smaller,

01:05:41.880 --> 01:05:50.150
it's totally devastated, so
as if area V4 were involved

01:05:50.150 --> 01:05:57.360
in the analysis of subtle
things, things which are lesser

01:05:57.360 --> 01:05:59.750
then, rather than
being reflex like

01:05:59.750 --> 01:06:04.640
and going to the brightest,
biggest thing in the world.

01:06:04.640 --> 01:06:12.270
OK, so that then indeed
highlights the fact

01:06:12.270 --> 01:06:13.970
that we have some
of these areas,

01:06:13.970 --> 01:06:17.850
including V4 and of
course, therefore MT,

01:06:17.850 --> 01:06:25.030
that involved in these much more
subtle types of visual analyses

01:06:25.030 --> 01:06:26.920
that we need to perform.

01:06:26.920 --> 01:06:34.350
Now capitalizing on these
kinds of subtle things

01:06:34.350 --> 01:06:37.670
that we are capable of doing,
artists, in addition to

01:06:37.670 --> 01:06:41.160
the ones that I've
shown you before, also

01:06:41.160 --> 01:06:48.210
created all kinds of percepts, I
should say paintings, sketches,

01:06:48.210 --> 01:06:54.730
precepts, that cause
confusion by playing around

01:06:54.730 --> 01:06:55.950
with these factors.

01:06:55.950 --> 01:07:01.345
One of these here is a very well
known audience called Escher.

01:07:03.350 --> 01:07:07.940
This was so near the
end of the 19th century.

01:07:07.940 --> 01:07:11.155
And here what we
have is this is sort

01:07:11.155 --> 01:07:13.740
of a figure-ground confusion.

01:07:13.740 --> 01:07:17.400
Here what we have is a bunch
of birds that fly to the right,

01:07:17.400 --> 01:07:20.060
and also a bunch of birds
that fly to the left.

01:07:20.060 --> 01:07:21.820
And so it's confusing.

01:07:21.820 --> 01:07:22.760
It's alternating.

01:07:22.760 --> 01:07:24.420
You don't know
which one is which.

01:07:24.420 --> 01:07:27.960
And it has to do with a
very, very clever creation

01:07:27.960 --> 01:07:31.370
of figure-ground confusions.

01:07:32.700 --> 01:07:36.220
And actually, next time
we talk about illusions,

01:07:36.220 --> 01:07:40.300
I will bring in some more of
these kinds of curious effects.

01:07:40.300 --> 01:07:42.980
And then here's another one.

01:07:42.980 --> 01:07:47.250
And it's very hard for you to
tell are the stairs going up?

01:07:47.250 --> 01:07:48.560
Are they going down?

01:07:48.560 --> 01:07:49.730
What's going on?

01:07:49.730 --> 01:07:56.590
It's the same kind of
play with the paintings

01:07:56.590 --> 01:07:59.990
to create confusion
in your perceptions.

01:07:59.990 --> 01:08:02.060
And then here is
yet another one,

01:08:02.060 --> 01:08:04.390
where you don't know
is water running up,

01:08:04.390 --> 01:08:06.280
or is the water
running down here?

01:08:06.280 --> 01:08:09.020
That's again an
interesting confusion

01:08:09.020 --> 01:08:11.360
that Escher has created.

01:08:11.360 --> 01:08:15.150
All right, so that
then is the essence

01:08:15.150 --> 01:08:20.200
of what I wanted to
cover today to highlight

01:08:20.200 --> 01:08:25.380
the fact that our
ability to extract shape

01:08:25.380 --> 01:08:30.410
information in the world
is absolutely incredible.

01:08:30.410 --> 01:08:33.479
And it has triggered
not only experiments

01:08:33.479 --> 01:08:36.640
to try to understand
that by scientists,

01:08:36.640 --> 01:08:41.810
but it has created a
tremendous amount of artwork

01:08:41.810 --> 01:08:46.979
that played with these
because it was so enjoyable.

01:08:46.979 --> 01:08:49.649
And certainly, the several
paintings that I have shown you

01:08:49.649 --> 01:08:51.630
must have given you
a pretty good sense

01:08:51.630 --> 01:08:57.660
of how artists capitalize on
these limitations in ability

01:08:57.660 --> 01:09:02.550
to extract intermediate
and high level vision

01:09:02.550 --> 01:09:05.490
capacities from
the visual scene.

01:09:05.490 --> 01:09:08.830
All right, so to summarize
them, first of all,

01:09:08.830 --> 01:09:12.470
I mentioned three
major theories that

01:09:12.470 --> 01:09:14.350
have to do with form processing.

01:09:14.350 --> 01:09:17.160
The one, the orientation
of line segments.

01:09:17.160 --> 01:09:19.840
And I pointed out to you
that that theory is not

01:09:19.840 --> 01:09:21.170
particularly powerful.

01:09:21.170 --> 01:09:24.979
And then the one, the
topographic theory,

01:09:24.979 --> 01:09:28.359
which turned out to be
bordering on the ridiculous.

01:09:28.359 --> 01:09:30.350
And finally, Fourier
analysis, which

01:09:30.350 --> 01:09:33.229
seems to have a lot of
power, even though it also

01:09:33.229 --> 01:09:35.740
has created a lot of skeptics.

01:09:35.740 --> 01:09:40.060
All right, then I pointed
out to that are the V2, V4,

01:09:40.060 --> 01:09:43.779
and inferotemporal cortex,
play important roles

01:09:43.779 --> 01:09:49.460
in intermediate vision, these
intermediate visual capacities

01:09:49.460 --> 01:09:51.640
we talked about in detail.

01:09:51.640 --> 01:09:57.020
Then I pointed out to
you also that in V2, it

01:09:57.020 --> 01:09:59.900
was discovered that there
are some neurons that

01:09:59.900 --> 01:10:06.170
respond to subjective contours,
indicating that already in area

01:10:06.170 --> 01:10:09.470
V2, we can perform these
incredibly higher level

01:10:09.470 --> 01:10:13.260
abilities to extract
information when

01:10:13.260 --> 01:10:15.850
it is unclear in
the visual scene.

01:10:15.850 --> 01:10:19.840
Then I pointed out to
you that recognition

01:10:19.840 --> 01:10:22.390
of objects transformed
in the various ways

01:10:22.390 --> 01:10:25.760
is compromised by V4 and
inferotemporal lesions.

01:10:25.760 --> 01:10:28.970
And V4 lesions also
produce major deficits

01:10:28.970 --> 01:10:34.100
in learning and selecting
lesser stimuli, which

01:10:34.100 --> 01:10:35.980
is a very important
attribute for us

01:10:35.980 --> 01:10:39.830
to be able not the respond
in reflex-like fashion

01:10:39.830 --> 01:10:41.490
to what is most
obvious out there,

01:10:41.490 --> 01:10:44.410
but to be able to
extract the subtle things

01:10:44.410 --> 01:10:46.300
from the visual scene.

01:10:46.300 --> 01:10:48.880
Some inferotemporal neurons
are selective for objects

01:10:48.880 --> 01:10:50.140
including faces.

01:10:50.140 --> 01:10:53.430
But most respond to a variety
of objects whose recognition is

01:10:53.430 --> 01:10:55.920
based on the
differential activity

01:10:55.920 --> 01:10:57.740
of a great many neurons.

01:10:58.820 --> 01:11:03.860
OK, so that then brings me
to the last point, which

01:11:03.860 --> 01:11:08.670
is how we process and deal
with ambiguities in perception,

01:11:08.670 --> 01:11:11.850
unfortunately still
remains a mystery.

01:11:11.850 --> 01:11:19.600
And so there's a lot of space
here for new investigators

01:11:19.600 --> 01:11:24.170
to come up with exciting,
interesting new findings

01:11:24.170 --> 01:11:31.440
about how the brain performs
these kinds of subtle analyses

01:11:31.440 --> 01:11:32.657
of the visual scene.

01:11:33.820 --> 01:11:38.250
OK, I think I'll leave
this until next time.

01:11:38.250 --> 01:11:39.635
I'll talk about this next time.

01:11:41.380 --> 01:11:43.891
OK, does anybody
have any questions?

01:11:47.820 --> 01:11:50.400
All right, I hope that you
can take a little bit of time

01:11:50.400 --> 01:11:53.540
out, look at some of these
artists on the internet,

01:11:53.540 --> 01:12:00.410
and look at Hirschfeld and the
Ninas that I had shown you.

